<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The ternary tests only for NULL but does not ensure 'key' points to a null-terminated object. If a caller supplies a non-NULL pointer that does not reference a NUL-terminated string (for example, a fixed-size buffer of length N filled with characters but no terminating '\0'), the strlen(key) operand will read past the bounds of that object and cause an out-of-bounds access. For instance, calling MHD_lookup_connection_value(connection, kind, key) with key pointing into header storage that is not NUL-terminated will make strlen invoke undefined behavior and violate Rule 21.17. Note: the code is safe only when all callers guarantee that any non-NULL key is a proper NUL-terminated string (e.g. string literals).
</scenario>
